Dwight Ripley. Poems, (Elkin Mathews & Marrot, 1931).;
Dwight Ripley. Spring Catalogue: A Poem, (Weekend Press, 1952).
Inscribed to Peggy Guggenheim by Dwight.;
Peggy Guggenheim. Out of This Century: The Informal Memoirs of Peggy Guggenheim,
(The Dial Press, 1946).
Inscribed to Dwight from Guggenheim. Dwight helped write Out of this Century and the
two also had a brief affair.;
Max Ernst and Paul Éluard. Translated by Hugh Chisolm. Misfortunes of the Immortals,
(Black Sun Press, 1943).
With inscription to Dwight from Peggy Guggenheim.;
Clement Greenberg. Joan Miró, (Quadrangle Press, 1948).
Inscribed to Dwight and Rupert by the author.;
Oscar Williams, ed. The War Poets: An Anthology of the War Poetry of the 20th Century,
(John Day, 1945).
Inscribed to Rupert by Willard Maas. Maas's love sonnet "Letter to Rupert' is published
as "Letter to R," in The War Poets. The two had a love affair, 1943–?.;
Willard Maas. Fire Testament, (Alecestis Press, 1935).
With inscription by the author to Rupert.;
Hugh Chisolm. Several Have Lived. Illustrations by André Masson, (The Gemor Press, 1942).
With inscriptions from Hugh Chisolm to George Barker and from Barker to Williard
Maas. Mass in turn gave the book to Dwight Ripley. It was then given to Rupert, who
gave it as a gift to Frank Polach.;
Card from Rupert Barneby to Frank Polach with provenance of Several Have Lived, 1991.;
H. Stuart Thompson's Flowering Plants of the Riviera (1914).
On the endpapers Dwight Ripley entered the itinerary for his and Rupert's Iberian trip,
ca. 1935 along with lists of species that would hopefully be collected for the gardens back
at Dwight's Sussex estate the Spinney. The book is a journal of their exploration and a
record of species.;
Janice C. Beatley. Vascular Plants of the Nevada Test Site and Central-Southern Nevada:
Ecologic and Geographic Distributions, (1976).
Inscription to Rupert from the author on card tipped in on f.f.e.;
Waddy Thompson and Estelle Ross. A Graphic History of the United States for
Young Readers (1920).
With an inscription to Master Rupert Barneby.;
The Published Writings of Philip Lutley Sclater, 1844–1896, (1896).
With TLS, laid in, from Rupert Barneby on Stirling House Stationery, 1962, explaining
that the books was passed on to him by his paternal grandmother, Sclater's sister.;
T.P Barneby. European Alpine Flowers in Colour, (Nelson, 1967).
Inscribed to Rupert and with ALS from the author.;
C.L. Baldwin. Quinquivara. (Gemor Press, [1944]).
3 botany books with information on Rupert Barneby and Dwight Ripley.;
